🇨🇦  **GenAI Genesis 2025**: **Canada's Largest AI Hackathon** 🧠 

Hey AI Enthusiasts! We're thrilled to invite you to GenAI Genesis 2025!
Whether you're **joining in person** at University of Toronto or **tuning in online** from anywhere around the globe, this is your chance to explore the future of AI.  🌐

**Event Details:**
📆 **Date**: March 21st (6 PM) to March 23rd (6 PM)
💻 **Format**: Online and In-Person
📍**Location**: University of Toronto Myhal Centre
🏆 **Prize Pool**: Over 10,000$ !
⏳ **Application Deadline**: March 8th, rolling basis

I’ve played with several of these, desperately hoping they’d work, but ultimately i came to the realization that if you want to take a step up from streamlit the best way to do that is with a regular javascript frontend framework. Every python framework is a wrapper translating into javascript, so there will always be strictly less functionality available in python. If you’re growing beyond streamlit now, you’ll likely grow beyond the next python framework as well, and then you’ll have an even more complex code base to migrate to javascript. That said, i do have a soft spot for fasthtml.

```
## What is Sundai
A global network of AI hackers who come together weekly to build, ship, and deploy AI applications in a single day. Unlike other tech meetups that focus on presentations, Sundai Hacks are about co-creating in teams to turn ideas into shipped products within 12 hours. 

Sundai is born out of MIT and Harvard.



## Attendee Screening Criteria 

Each Attendee Must Be Able To "Actively Build": 
- **Code** - ability to code or a commitment to 
- **Team** - build in a team and bring positive value (and vibe) 
- **Ship** - focus on deploying a user-facing application by end of the day 

### Commitment Requirements:
- **Full day participation* - 10am-10pm or equivalent. Drop offs highly discouraged as it breaks team dynamic. 
- **Sundai projects only** - work on ideas born at sundai hacks, not personal projects from before
- **Community contribution** - help with setup/cleanup. We are all volunteers. Everyone helps to run the event. 
- **Attribution** - post projects on sundai.club/projects and clearly display 'Built at Sundai' on website or demos (e.g. footer, etc) 


- **Pre-Launch Checklist (7-8pm)**:
  - Open source code on GitHub
  - Create project page on sundai.club
  - Write blog/vlog documentation
  - Post on social media (minimum LinkedIn)
  
- **Launch (8-9pm)** - live user testing, not pitch presentations. Team shares with community about which new tools they tried and what worked / didnt work. 



```

Hello @everyone our group is working on the 'perfect' Sundai Card template and a way to incentivize voting on the 'best' hacks at the end of the day. 

Sundai will post your card and promote your project for you on social media so that you can get some public exposure and notoriety for your 12 hours of hard work and your project will be featured at the top of the project list on the website. 

In order to have the most impact when Sundai posts your app, in addition to filling out the card in its ENTIRETY, you should have a 2 minute demo video discussing FEATURES and TOOL INSIGHTS, and a DEPLOYED LIVE LINK so users can quickly and effortlessly use it. All this can be placed in the card and your demo video can be used at the end of day leaving questions to cover the live portion.

Deploying and creating a good card takes time and will siphon off building minutes, so if you need help doing it, let me know and I can pitch in just ping me.

Much like Hacker Combinator is an effort to turn our projects into real world stuff, this small move will help projects gain traction in the real world so let's all work together and continue to push ourselves into the realm of practicality.
